<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-101-140  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 101 140.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Feb 20 1989 v6 n7 p17(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Text retrieval system runs on new DEC PCs. (Excalibur Technologiesneural network software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Excalibur Technologies offers neural network software, the SavvyVision Recognition System (VRS) and the Savvy Text RetrievalSystem (TRS).andP;  VRS locates, tracks and recognizes objects in realtime.andP;  A maximum of 1,024 objects can be recognized.andP;  VRS pricesare $45,000; a run-time license for over 50 users is $15,000.andP;  TRSfinds close matches in text, giving users the ability to findinformation by using fragmented phrases.andP;  TRS is priced from$8,000 to $44,000.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Excalibur Technologies Corp. (product development).andO;Product:   Savvy Text Retrieval System (Computer program) (productspecifications)Savvy Vision Recognition System (Compter program) (productspecifications)DEC MicroVAX (Minicomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Neural NetworksSoftware PackagesReal-Time Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Text Retrieval System Runs on New DEC PCsandM;ALBUQUERQUE, N.M.andP;  -- Excalibur Technologies has put its neural networksoftware on DEC's new DECstation 386 PC to bring together a computer systemthat learns to recognize objects and text lines and reacts to what it &quot;sees.&quot;andM;Excalibur's Savvy Vision Recognition System (VRS) locates, recognizes, andtracks objects in real time.andM;The Savvy Text Retrieval System (TRS) finds close matches in text, enablingthe user to find information using fragmented phrases and mispelled words.andM;With a combination of the two neural net programs and a DEC-station 386 or aMicroVAX, users can store and retrieve pictures along with documents.andM;Excalibur is an OEM for the DEC machines and sells both the hardware andsoftware for complete Savvy/VRS systems.andM;The Savvy/VRS uses 18 functions written in C, and the Savvy/TRS uses 17functions.andM;The Savvy/VRS system &quot;can be trained to recognize a maximum of 1,024different objects,&quot; Excalibur Executive Vice President Pat Patterson said.andO;&quot;They can be totally different objects--screwdrivers, wrenches, bikes, faces,animals, ships, planes--just whatever you take a picture of.&quot;andM;When the system sees an object it has previously been shown, it compares theold image with the new one to determine if they are the same.andM;The system can be set for a 100 percent pass, 99.5 percent pass, 95 percentpass, or whatever the customer wants, Patterson said.andM;Similarly, the text retrieval system can be set to point out phrases in thetext that match to varying degrees what the user types in.andM;The Savvy/TRS software ranges from $8,000 to $44,000, depending on thesystem.andP;  The Savvy/VRS system is priced at $45,000; run-time licenses forover 50 users are priced at $15,000 each.andM;The hardware includes a DEC-station with 2MB of memory and an 80MB drive,camera, and frame grabber, and is priced at an additional $12,000.andM;Excalibur Technologies Corp. is located at 2300 Buena Vista Southeast,Albuquerque, NM 87106, (505) 764-0081.andO;</TEXT></DOC>